## Estimates

### How do I create an estimate?

From a job's detail page, tap **Estimates → +**. Give it a title, set your tax and contingency rates, then add line items. Each line item has a category (Materials, Labor, Equipment, Subcontractor, Permit, or Other), a description, quantity, unit, and unit price.

### How is the estimate total calculated?

The calculation is: **Subtotal** (sum of all line items) + **Contingency** (subtotal × contingency rate) = **Taxable Amount**. Then **Tax** (taxable amount × tax rate) is added to get the **Grand Total**.

### What does contingency mean?

Contingency is a percentage buffer (default 10%) added to the subtotal to cover unexpected costs. You can set it to 0% if you don't need it. The percentage is entered as a whole number (e.g., "10" for 10%).

### How do I send an estimate to a client?

Tap **Generate Estimate PDF** at the bottom of the estimate builder. This creates a professional PDF you can share via email, text, AirDrop, or any share method on your phone. When you dismiss the share sheet, the estimate is automatically marked as "Sent" with a timestamp.

### What do the estimate statuses mean?

- **Draft** — Created but not yet sent to the client.
- **Sent** — The PDF has been shared with the client (or manually marked Sent).
- **Accepted** — The client approved the estimate.
- **Declined** — The client rejected it. You can record a reason (Cost Too High, No Budget, Changed Mind, Lost to Competitor, etc.) and additional notes.

### Can a customer sign the estimate?

Yes. The estimate builder has a **Customer Signature** section where you can capture the client's signature. They can sign directly on screen (draw mode) or you can photograph a signed copy (photo mode). The signature, name, and date appear on the PDF.

### What happens to estimates when I mark a job Complete?

Any Draft or Sent estimates are automatically changed to "Accepted" since the job was clearly approved. This keeps your pipeline analytics accurate.

